\PYG{l+s+sb}{```}
\PYG{l+s+sb}{The G√∂del sentence \PYGZdl{}G\PYGZdl{} functions as another instance of the null representation. It represents that which enables the system (the capacity for truth) while remaining unrepresentable \PYGZbs{}textit\PYGZob{}within\PYGZcb{} the system (unprovable). Like Kant\PYGZsq{}s transcendental \PYGZsq{}I,\PYGZsq{} Habermas\PYGZsq{}s intent to communicate, and Agamben\PYGZsq{}s Voice, \PYGZdl{}G\PYGZdl{} belongs to the equivalence class of enabling conditions that cannot be captured by what they enable.}
\PYG{l+s+sb}{```}

\PYG{g+gu}{\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{} Connect to Diagonalization}
\PYG{l+s+sb}{```}
\PYG{l+s+sb}{Diagonalization is the formal technique underlying G√∂del\PYGZsq{}s construction of \PYGZdl{}G\PYGZdl{}. Just as Cantor used diagonalization to demonstrate that the real numbers exceed any enumeration, G√∂del used it to construct a statement exceeding any finite proof system. This same technique appears throughout the manuscript‚Äîin Russell\PYGZsq{}s paradox, in the \PYGZbs{}\PYGZob{}I\PYGZbs{}\PYGZcb{}/\PYGZsq{}me\PYGZsq{} distinction, in the structure of self\PYGZhy{}consciousness itself. Diagonalization is the mathematical expression of self\PYGZhy{}transcendence.}
\PYG{l+s+sb}{```}

\PYG{g+gu}{\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{}\PYGZsh{} Connect to Euclid\PYGZsq{}s Prime Proof}
\PYG{l+s+sb}{```}
\PYG{l+s+sb}{When students grasp Euclid\PYGZsq{}s proof that there are infinitely many primes, they enact precisely the kind of meta\PYGZhy{}reasoning required to recognize the truth of the G√∂del sentence. Euclid\PYGZsq{}s proof reasons \PYGZbs{}textit\PYGZob{}about\PYGZcb{} the number system from a vantage outside any finite list of primes. The \PYGZsq{}I\PYGZsq{} that grasps this proof transcends the \PYGZsq{}me\PYGZsq{} that can enumerate any particular finite set. This is mathematical thinking as self\PYGZhy{}transcendence.}
\PYG{l+s+sb}{```}

